<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="I"><UNDER>AMENDED</UNDER> NOTICE OF APPEAL</TI>
<P><UNDER><BOLD>THE APPELLANT</BOLD> amends the Notice of Appeal dated April 27, 2018, from the judgment of Madam Justice Sylvia Corthorn dated March 28, 2018. This Amended Notice of Appeal shall be read in conjunction with the Supplementary Notice of Appeal dated June 6, 2018, seeking leave to appeal the costs endorsement of Madam Justice Sylvia Corthorn, dated May 22, 2018.</UNDER></P>
<P><BOLD>THE PLAINTIFF APPEALS</BOLD> to the Court of Appeal from the judgment of Madam Justice Sylvia Corthorn dated March 28, 2018, made at Ottawa.</P>
<P><BOLD>THE APPELLANT ASKS</BOLD> that the judgment be varied to include:</P>
<P>1. The Appellant is entitled to reasonable notice at common law of the termination of his employment in the amount of 22 months.</P>
<P><BOLD>THE APPELLANT</BOLD> further requests:</P>
<P>2. The Appellant be granted its costs of the appeal on a substantial indemnity basis;</P>
<P>3. Such further and other relief as counsel may advise and this Honourable Court may permit.</P>
<P><BOLD>THE GROUNDS OF APPEAL</BOLD> are as follows:</P>
<P>1. The motion judge determined that 22 months is an appropriate reasonable notice period for the Appellant, but concluded that he did not have an entitlement to reasonable notice of the termination of his employment.</P>
<P>2. The motion judge erred in law and in mixed law and fact in making the determination that the Appellant did not have an entitlement to reasonable notice of the termination of his employment; specifically, she failed to consider in her legal analysis material factual elements and legal arguments that were before her. A summary of these facts is as follows:</P>
<P>3. During the course of his employment as an architect with the Respondent, the Appellant wished to reduce his work to part time hours in or around the spring of 2013.</P>
<P>4. The parties negotiated terms of part time employment for the Appellant, including, at the Respondent's insistence, that the Appellant resign from full time hours and waive his entitlement to termination and severance pay for his previous years of service. They also agreed that his entitlement upon termination would be limited to his <EM>Employment Standards Act (&ldquo;ESA&rdquo;)</EM> entitlements commencing from his part time start date.</P>
<P>5. The Appellant commenced working part time in or around July 15, 2013, having negotiated the above respecting the termination of his employment.</P>
<P>6. To satisfy the Respondent's requirements, on July 17, 2013, the Appellant provided the Respondent a letter resigning from full time employment, indicating that the new employment terms would be in accordance with the Employment Standards Act of Ontario, but that termination, notice and severance for his past employment would not form part of the new terms of employment.</P>
<P>7. After he provided this to the Respondent and had been working under these terms, he was presented with an employment contract dated July 24, 2013, purporting to apply retroactively to July 15, 2013, which indicated that &ldquo;Either party may terminate this agreement by providing the minimum notice required under the Employment Standards Act of Ontario.&rdquo;</P>
<P>8. When the Appellant's employment was terminated in January 2016, he was provided with three and a half weeks of working notice, two weeks of benefit continuation, and no severance pay, consistent with the waiver of termination and severance pay for years of service prior to July 15, 2013. He was advised by the Respondent that this was more than his <EM>Employment Standards Act</EM> entitlements.</P>
<P>9. The motion judge determined that the Appellant had nearly 30 years of continuous service at the time of his dismissal and that his <EM>ESA</EM> entitlements at the time were eight weeks of termination pay and 26 weeks of severance pay.</P>
<P>10. <STRIKE>The motion judge erred in mixed law and fact in failing to find that the Respondent intended that the Appellant resign from his employment, thus creating a break in service.</STRIKE> <UNDER>The motion judge erred in law by failing to determine that the agreed upon resignation from his full-time position to take on a part-time position entitled the Appellant to a common law entitlement to reasonable notice of the termination of his employment.</UNDER> In any case, she erred in law by failing to determine that the agreed upon waiver of termination and severance pay for previous years of service entitled him to a common law entitlement to reasonable notice of the termination of his employment, <UNDER>as did the agreement to provide him with his entitlements under the ESA from the start date of the part-time contract only.</UNDER></P>
<P>11. The motion judge erred in law in considering the parties' intentions to limit to <EM>ESA</EM> minimums <STRIKE>when such intention is void</STRIKE> in the face of an express contracting out of the legislation. <UNDER>She failed to consider their intention to contract out of the legislation.</UNDER></P>
<P>12. The motion judge erred in law in reviewing <UNDER>the historical termination provision</UNDER> <STRIKE>written terms of the contract</STRIKE> to determine the Plaintiff's entitlements, rather than the earlier negotiated terms. Or, in the alternative, the motion judge <STRIKE>erred in reviewing</STRIKE> <UNDER>failed to review</UNDER> the termination provision in the subsequent written contract in <STRIKE>isolation</STRIKE> <UNDER>the context</UNDER> of the waiver of termination and severance pay for previous years of service, and in <STRIKE>isolation</STRIKE> the context of the start date of the contract.</P>
<P>13. <UNDER>Alternatively,</UNDER> the motion judge erred in the determination that consideration was not relevant to the Appellant's termination entitlements. The Appellant was already working under agreed upon terms of part time employment by the time the written contract was presented to him. To the extent that the written contract had less favourable termination entitlements, which limited to statutory minimums only, <STRIKE>as the motion judge found</STRIKE>, <UNDER>which is denied</UNDER>, he received no consideration for accepting those terms.</P>
<P>14. The motion judge erred in allowing the Respondent to rely upon <UNDER>an unlawful contract</UNDER> a <STRIKE>termination provision</STRIKE> that they did not honour or intend to honour, particularly where <UNDER>the</UNDER> outcome was that the Appellant received less than his statutory minimum entitlements.</P>
<P>15. THE BASIS OF THE APPELLATE COURT'S JURISDICTION IS:
<P1>(a) Section 6(1)(b) of the <EM>Courts of Justice Act</EM>, R.S.O. 1990 c.43;</P1>
<P1>(b) Rule 61 of the <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM>;</P1>
<P1>(c) The Order appealed from is final;</P1>
<P1>(d) Leave to appeal is not required.</P1></P>
<P>The Appellant requests that this appeal be heard at the Court of Appeal for Ontario, located at 130 Queen Street West, Toronto, Ontario.</P>
