<BLOCK1><TI>NOTICE OF CROSS-APPEAL</TI>
<P><BOLD>THE RESPONDENT CROSS-APPEALS</BOLD> in this appeal from the judgment of the Honourable Justice Corthorn dated March 28, 2018, and asks that the judgment be varied to include the following:</P>
<P>1. The Appellant breached his obligation to mitigate his damages and, if the Appellant is entitled to damages in excess of his statutory entitlement, the damages must be reduced accordingly;</P>
<P>2. Had the Appellant been entitled to notice at common law of the termination of his employment, the reasonable notice period is not 22 months, but a lesser amount to account for the Appellant's failure to mitigate his damages;</P>
<P>3. An Order compelling the Appellant to pay to the Respondent its costs of the appeal and this cross-appeal on a substantial indemnity basis; and</P>
<P>4. Such further and other relief as counsel may advise and this Honourable Court may permit be granted.</P>
<P><BOLD>THE GROUNDS FOR THIS CROSS-APPEAL</BOLD> are as follows:</P>
<P>1. The motion judge held that the terms of the Appellant's contract of employment with the Respondent do not include entitlement to notice of termination of his employment without cause based on the common law, and that the Appellant was therefore entitled to his statutory entitlement of eight weeks' notice of the termination of his employment;</P>
<P>2. The motion judge erred in fact and in law in finding that, had the Appellant been entitled to common law notice of the termination of his employment, the reasonable notice period would be 22 months;</P>
<P>3. The motion judge erred in law by making a determination on the Appellant's reasonable notice period, had he been entitled to common law notice of the termination of his employment, but failing to address the issue of mitigation;</P>
<P>4. The motion judge erred in law and fact by failing to find that the Appellant breached his obligation to mitigate damages and by failing to reduce the damages to which the Appellant would be entitled to, if the damages exceeded his statutory entitlement; and</P>
<P>5. Such further and other grounds as counsel may advise and this Honourable Court may permit.</P>
