<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="I">PART I&mdash;SUMMARY OF PROCEEDINGS</TI>
<P>1. In her Order dated March 28, 2018 from a summary judgment motion in the Superior Court of Justice, Corthorn J. found that the Appellant, John David Ariss (&ldquo;Ariss&rdquo;) had a statutory entitlement under the <EM>Employment Standards Act</EM> (&ldquo;<EM>ESA</EM>&rdquo;) to eight weeks of termination pay and 26 weeks of severance pay in connection with the termination of his employment with the Respondent employer, NORR Limited Architects and Engineers, (&ldquo;NORR&rdquo;); however, she found the presumption of reasonable notice of termination of employment had been rebutted.</P>
<P>2. In her subsequent Order of May 22, 2018, Corthorn J. awarded costs to Respondent in the amount of $20,390, in accordance with Rule 49.10(2) of the <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM> and the March 28, 2018 Order.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="II">PART II&mdash;OVERVIEW</TI>
<BLOCK3><TI><EM>Machtinger</EM> incorrectly applied</TI>
<P>3. In determining that the presumption of reasonable notice had been rebutted, the motion judge relied upon the Supreme Court of Canada's decision in <CASEREF><SOC>Machtinger v. HOJ Industries Ltd.</SOC><YEAR>1992</YEAR><CITE>1992 CanLII 102</CITE><COURTJUR>SCC</COURTJUR></CASEREF> <BOLD>[<EM>Machtinger</EM>]</BOLD> for the principle that a reasonable notice entitlement is rebuttable if the contract of employment clearly specifies some other period of notice, expressly or impliedly. She reiterated reliance upon this decision in her costs endorsement of May 22, 2018.</P>
<P>4. The Appellant states that the motion judge erred in applying <BOLD><EM>Machtinger</EM></BOLD> by failing to consider the qualifying provisions therein that if the intention of the parties is to make an unlawful contract, no lawful contractual term can be derived from that intention and that if an employment contract fails to comply with the minimum statutory notice provisions of the <EM>ESA</EM>, then the presumption of reasonable notice will not have been rebutted.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI>Reasonable Notice Entitlement</TI>
<P>5. The Respondent would only move the Appellant from full-time to part-time employment if he: (a) agreed to resign from his full-time position; (b) agreed to waive his entitlement to termination and severance pay for his previous years of service; and (c) agreed to limit his entitlements under the <EM>ESA</EM> to those accrued after the start date of the new part-time contract. The Appellant commenced part-time employment on July 15, 2013, and provided a letter confirming those terms on July 17, 2013:
<QUOTE><P>Please accept this letter as notice of my wishes to reduce my work week and resign from my full time position as Senior Architect from the NORR Kingston Office. This is conditional on acceptance of a new offer of employment for part time hours, conditions which have been discussed with and agreed to by Brian Gerstmar.</P>
<P>I understand that the new employment terms will be in accordance with the Employment Standards Act of Ontario. Termination, notice and severance for my past employment will not form part of the new terms of employment.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>6. He was subsequently provided a part-time employment contract with a retroactive start date of July 15, 2013, which stipulated that, &ldquo;Either party may terminate this agreement by providing the minimum notice required under the Employment Standards Act of Ontario.&rdquo; He signed on July 31, 2013.</P>
<P>7. The motion judge declined to determine whether the parties had agreed to terms of part-time employment prior to executing the 2013 employment contract and whether the contract had terms of dismissal that differed from the earlier negotiated terms.</P>
<P>8. Accepting the Respondent's evidence that the terms of employment were agreed upon before part-time work commenced, the negotiated terms of dismissal contracted out of the <EM>ESA</EM>. If the subsequent contract is seen to capture the same terms, then it must be read in the light of the start date for <EM>ESA</EM> entitlements being July 15, 2013, the resignation from full-time employment, and waiver of termination and severance pay for previous years of service provided by the Appellant. Both result in a reasonable notice entitlement.</P>
<P>9. If the subsequent contract captured different terms, and successfully rebuts the reasonable notice presumption, which we deny, then there was no consideration for its acceptance.</P>
<P>10. Upon his dismissal in January 2016, Ariss was provided three and a half weeks of termination pay, two weeks of benefits, and no severance pay and advised that he was being provided more than his statutory entitlements. This is consistent with NORR's reliance upon a resignation from his full-time position, waiver of termination and severance pay for years of service prior to July 2013, and the agreement to commence <EM>ESA</EM> entitlements as of July 15, 2013 only.</P>
<P>11. Corthorn J. ruled that he had continuous service with NORR commencing in 1986 and that the Respondent failed to provide him eight weeks' notice and 26 weeks' severance pay in accordance with the <EM>Employment Standards Act</EM>.</P>
<P>12. In her analysis of the parties' intentions, the motion judge reviewed earlier contracts between them as evidence that they wished to rebut the reasonable notice presumption; however this was done in error as she failed to consider the impact of the intention to contract out of the <EM>ESA</EM> and the act of so doing in 2013. In such case, a reasonable notice entitlement flows.</P>
<P>13. NORR intended to contract out of the <EM>ESA</EM> with respect to Ariss' entitlements upon dismissal, contracted out of the <EM>ESA</EM> with respect to Ariss' entitlements upon dismissal, provided less than Ariss' <EM>ESA</EM> entitlements upon his dismissal, and the only consequence to NORR was payment of those <EM>ESA</EM> minimum entitlements. This runs afoul of the principles articulated in <BOLD><EM>Machtinger</EM>.</BOLD></P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="III">PART III&mdash;FACTS</TI>
<P>14. Ariss' service as an employee with NORR and its predecessors commenced in February 1986 and remained continuous throughout a sale of business and his transition from full-time to part-time employment.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Ariss v. NORR Limited Architects &amp; Engineers</SOC><CITE>2018 ONSC 620</CITE></CASEREF> <BOLD>[Judgment], para 39 and 96 at Appeal Book and Compendium [ABCO] Tab 7, p. 35 and 46.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>15. The parties engaged in lengthy negotiations surrounding Ariss' transition from full-time to part-time employment in 2013. Notably, NORR refused to move Ariss to part-time employment unless he agreed to resign from his full-time position and waive termination and severance entitlements for his past years of employment. This is articulated repeatedly in the Respondent's evidence:
<QUOTE><P>NORR would not have agreed to the part-time employment agreement terms that it did with Mr. Ariss unless he agreed to resign and waive his past years of termination and severance entitlements.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD>Affidavit of Brian Gerstmar, sworn March 10, 2017, [Gerstmar Affidavit], para 13, at ABCO Tab 15, p. 146 and Exhibit Book [EB] Tab 3, p. 143.</BOLD></P1>
<QUOTE><P>I would never have agreed to the generous terms of his new part-time position if he had not agreed to resign and waive his past years of termination and severance entitlements.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD>Affidavit of Jacqui Souter, sworn March 10, 2017, [Souter Affidavit], para 24, at ABCO Tab 14, p. 116 and EB Tab 2, p. 68.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>16. This was relayed to Ariss before he started part-time work:
<QUOTE><P>In my e-mail, I made clear that NORR would only agree to Mr. Ariss' part-time work arrangement if he gave up any of his notice and severance entitlements for his past years of service with NORR, which was from November 2002 until May 2013. I also made clear in my email that, going forward as a part-time employee, Mr. Ariss would accrue notice and severance entitlements in accordance with the ESA.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD>Souter Affidavit, para 17, at ABCO Tab 14, p. 113 and EB Tab 2, p. 65.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>Souter Affidavit Exhibit E, at ABCO Tab 14E, p. 122 and EB Tab 2E, p. 98 / Gerstmar Affidavit Exhibit B at ABCO Tab 15B, p. 148 and EB Tab 3B, p. 149.</BOLD></P1>
<QUOTE><P>I asked Mr. Gerstmar to call Mr. Ariss to make clear to Mr. Ariss that his transition to this new position would require his resignation and waiver of his past years' termination and severance entitlements. I believe that in late June 2013, Mr. Gerstmar conveyed this message to Mr. Ariss by phone.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD>Souter Affidavit, para 18, at ABCO Tab 14, p. 114 and EB Tab 2, p. 66</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>Judgment, para 57, at ABCO Tab 7, p. 40.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>17. The parties contemplated providing Ariss with his entitlements under the <EM>ESA</EM> commencing from the start date of his part-time employment only. While he sought in negotiations to change those terms, NORR was adamant that they were material:
<QUOTE><P>My transition to a reduction in work hours would not interrupt my continuous employment service for the purpose of maintaining company benefit entitlements and government regulated compensation rights, including severance and termination.</P>
<P><BOLD>Not Agreed</BOLD>&mdash;Since you are voluntarily retiring from your full time employment, you will no longer be eligible for any notice or severance pay for your years of service from November 2002 to May 2013. You will accrue years of service for notice and severance in accordance with the Employment Standards Act, as of your casual start date of July 1<SUP>st</SUP> 2013.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD>Souter Affidavit Exhibit E, at ABCO Tab 14E, p. 122 and EB Tab 2E, p. 98 / Gerstmar Affidavit Exhibit B at ABCO Tab 15B, p. 148 and EB Tab 3B, p. 149.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>Souter Affidavit Exhibit F, at ABCO Tab 14F, p. 133 and EB Tab 2F, p. 109 / Gerstmar Affidavit Exhibit C, at ABCO Tab 15C, p. 158 and EB Tab 3C, p. 159.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>Judgment para 55 at ABCO Tab 7, p. 39.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>18. Ariss understood that NORR would not do a deal to allow him to work part-time unless he started &ldquo;fresh:&rdquo;
<QUOTE><P>Q. That was the position that NORR was taking. They said, &ldquo;We're not prepared to continue to honour your service. You had to start fresh if you were going to go to part-time.&rdquo; The service entitlements accrual would begin when you started part-time. That was NORR's position, correct?</P>
<P>A. Yes.</P>
<P>Q. You understood that that position was being conveyed in a way that was not negotiable as of July 4, 2013, correct?</P>
<P>A. Yes</P></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD>Cross-Examination of John David Ariss, conducted April 24, 2017, [Ariss Cross], p. 28, Q 178,179), at ABCO Tab 11, p. 75 and EB Tab 7, p. 208.</BOLD></P1>
<QUOTE><P>Q. You understood that unless you resigned and agreed that for the purpose of any notice, it started again with the new position starting date, the new part-time position starting date?</P>
<P>A. That was their position.</P>
<P>Q. And you understood, I'm going to put to you one more thing, you understood that they would not agree to do a part-time deal with you unless you agreed to those terms, correct?</P>
<P>A. Yes.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD>Ariss Cross, P. 32; Q. 198, 199, at ABCO Tab 11, p. 76 and EB Tab 7, p. 212.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>19. Accepting the Respondent's evidence that all terms of the move to part-time employment were agreed upon by July 11, 2013, including his agreement to resign from his full-time position, Ariss then commenced part-time work on July 15, 2013.
<P1><BOLD>Souter Affidavit, para 20, at ABCO Tab 14, p. 114 and EB Tab 2, p. 66.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>Affidavit of John David Ariss, sworn January 9, 2017, [Ariss Affidavit], para 20, at ABCO Tab 12, p. 80 and EB Tab 1, p. 4.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>20. Consistent with the parties' agreement, Ariss provided NORR with a letter at their request stating the following on July 17, 2013:
<QUOTE><P>Please accept this letter as notice of my wishes to reduce my work week and resign from my full time position as Senior Architect from the NORR Kingston Office. This is conditional on acceptance of a new offer of employment for part time hours, conditions which have been discussed with and agreed to by Brian Gerstmar.</P>
<P>I understand that the new employment terms will be in accordance with the Employment Standards Act of Ontario. Termination, notice and severance for my past employment will not form part of the new terms of employment.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD>Ariss Affidavit Exhibit E, at ABCO Tab 12E, p. 90 and EB Tab 1E, p. 24.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>Affidavit of John David Ariss, sworn March 28, 2017, [Ariss Reply Affidavit], para 15 and 16, at ABCO Tab 13, p. 101 and EB Tab 4, p. 162.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>21. Ariss subsequently was provided a contract with a retroactive start date of July 15, 2013, which he signed on July 31, 2013. It read in part: &ldquo;Either party may terminate this agreement by providing the minimum notice required under the Employment Standards Act of Ontario.&rdquo;
<P1><BOLD>Ariss Affidavit para 23, 24 at ABCO Tab 12, p. 80, 81 and EB Tab 1, p. 4, 5.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>Ariss Affidavit Exhibit F, at ABCO Tab 12F, p. 92 and EB Tab 1F, p. 26.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>Souter Affidavit Exhibit H, at ABCO Tab 14H, p. 136 and EB Tab 2H, p. 112.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>Judgment para 68, 69 at ABCO Tab 7, p. 42.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>22. The motion judge looked at the &ldquo;historical termination provision&rdquo; in contracts that the parties negotiated in 2002 and 2006 to demonstrate an ongoing intention that the reasonable notice presumption be rebutted.
<P1><BOLD>Judgment para 77, 78, 79, at ABCO Tab 7, p. 43, 44.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>23. Neither the negotiations respecting the move to part-time work, nor the subsequent contract that followed made express reference to the &ldquo;historical termination provision,&rdquo; consisting of a chart of termination entitlements described by the motion judge.
<P1><BOLD>Judgment para 79 at ABCO Tab 7, p. 44.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>Ariss Affidavit Exhibit F at ABCO Tab 12F, p. 92 and EB Tab 1F, p. 26.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>Souter Affidavit Exhibit I, at ABCO Tab 14I, p. 140 and EB Tab 2I, p. 116.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>24. Due to her finding on the clarity of the historical termination provision in limiting to the minimum entitlements under the <EM>ESA</EM>, the motion judge did not determine whether the negotiated terms of part-time employment and the subsequent contract contained the same terms. Accordingly, she did not determine which terms governed Ariss' employment upon dismissal, or determine whether consideration flowed if there was a legal waiver of reasonable notice entitlements in the July 31, 2013 contract, which is denied.
<P1><BOLD>Judgment para 80, 81, at ABCO Tab 7, p. 44.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>25. Upon his dismissal in January 2016, NORR gave Ariss 3.5 weeks' notice of termination and offered to continue Ariss' benefits for a period of two weeks following the effective date of termination. NORR did not provide Ariss with severance pay.
<P1><BOLD>Judgment para 11, at ABCO Tab 7, p. 29.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>Ariss Affidavit Exhibit K, at ABCO Tab 12K, p. 96 and EB Tab 1K, p. 30.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>26. In 2016, NORR was of the view that (a) Ariss was entitled to only two weeks' notice pursuant to the <EM>ESA</EM>, and (b) it had, by giving Ariss 3.5 weeks' notice, exceeded its statutory obligation for notice of termination.
<P1><BOLD>Judgment para 13 at ABCO Tab 7, p. 30.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>Souter Affidavit para 30 at ABCO Tab 14, p. 117 and EB Tab 2, p. 69.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>27. Ariss' actual statutory entitlements amounted to eight weeks of termination pay and 26 weeks of severance pay, based on nearly 30 years of continuous service.
<P1><BOLD>Judgment para 117 at ABCO Tab 7, p. 49.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>28. While she determined that the presumption of reasonable notice had been rebutted, the motion judge found that the appropriate period of reasonable notice was 22 months, had there been an entitlement to it.
<P1><BOLD>Judgment para 117 at ABCO Tab 7, p. 49.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>29. Given that there was not an award of reasonable notice, Corthorn J. ordered Ariss to pay NORR $20,390 in costs in accordance with Rule 49.10(2) of the <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM>.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Ariss v. NORR Limited Architects &amp; Engineers</SOC><CITE>2018 ONSC 3157</CITE></CASEREF><BOLD>, [&ldquo;Costs endorsement&rdquo;], Para 16, 25, 26, at ABCO Tab 8, p. 54, 55.</BOLD></P1></P>
<BLOCK3><TI>Reliance upon <EM>Machtinger</EM></TI>
<P>30. The motion judge applied <BOLD><EM>Machtinger</EM></BOLD> in determining that the common law presumption of entitlement to reasonable notice had been rebutted.
<P1><BOLD>Judgment para 73 and 74, at ABCO Tab 7, p. 43.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>31. In her costs endorsement, in addressing the issue of whether Ariss had contracted out of his reasonable notice entitlement, she again noted that, &ldquo;In deciding this issue, I applied the law as set out in <CASEREF><SOC>Machtinger v. HOJ Industries Ltd.</SOC><YEAR>1992</YEAR><CITE>1992 CanLII 102</CITE><COURTJUR>SCC</COURTJUR><CASEHIST><CASEREF><CITE>[1992] 1 S.C.R. 986</CITE></CASEREF></CASEHIST></CASEREF>.&rdquo;
<P1><BOLD>Costs endorsement para 23, at ABCO Tab 8, p. 55.</BOLD></P1></P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="IV">PART IV&mdash;STATEMENT OF ISSUES, LAW, AND AUTHORITIES</TI>
<BLOCK3><TI>Issues:</TI>
<P>32. Did the motion judge incorrectly apply <BOLD><EM>Machtinger</EM>?</BOLD>
<P1>a) What is the standard of review?</P1>
<P1>b) Did the parties intend to contract out of minimum <EM>ESA</EM> entitlements respecting termination of employment, giving rise to a reasonable notice entitlement?</P1>
<P1>c) Did the parties in fact contract out of minimum <EM>ESA</EM> entitlements respecting termination of employment, giving rise to a reasonable notice entitlement?</P1>
<P1>d) Did the motion judge accordingly err in looking at the intention of the parties to rebut the reasonable notice entitlement?</P1></P>
<P>33. If the Appellant has a reasonable notice entitlement, should leave be granted to vary the Costs endorsement so that costs in the first instance follow the event and Rule 49 of the <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM>?</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI>Law and Authorities:</TI>
<BLOCK4><TI><UNDER><EM>Standard of Review</EM></UNDER></TI>
<P>34. As she looked only at the legal question of whether or not the parties intended to limit the Appellant's entitlements upon dismissal, the motion judge did not look at qualifying legal questions of whether or not the parties intended to contract out of the <EM>ESA</EM> and whether they did so. In order to determine those qualifying questions of law, facts that were before the judge, and which are not materially in dispute, must be applied. To make the determination of whether the parties contracted out of the <EM>ESA</EM>, the Court may be required to make a legal finding on consideration based on those facts; the motion judge declined to make this determination in light of her findings on the first question.</P>
<P>35. In the context of contractual interpretation, &ldquo;the application of an incorrect principle, the failure to consider a required element of a legal test, or the failure to consider a relevant factor&rdquo; has been characterized as an error of law. The failure to consider relevant factors in the determination of whether or not the reasonable notice presumption has been rebutted, as outlined in <BOLD><EM>Machtinger</EM>,</BOLD> falls into this category, attracting a correctness standard of review.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Creston Moly Corp. v. Sattva Capital Corp</SOC><CITE>2014 SCC 53</CITE></CASEREF><BOLD>, [<EM>Sattva</EM>], para 53.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Housen v. Nikolaisen</SOC><CITE>2002 SCC 33</CITE></CASEREF> <BOLD>[<EM>Hausen</EM>], para 8, 31, 34, 35.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>36. While this appeal raises questions of mixed fact and law, which standard of review falls on a spectrum between correctness and overriding error, it can be seen as primarily an error of law.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Housen</EM> para 8 and 36.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>37. The instant matter can be characterized as having extricable errors of law in the failure to consider whether the parties intended to contract out of the <EM>ESA</EM> and whether the termination entitlements contracted out of the <EM>ESA visa-vis</EM> the facts, confirming the correctness standard.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Housen</EM> paras 33&ndash;36.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Holland v. Hostopia.com Inc.</SOC><CITE>2015 ONCA 762</CITE></CASEREF><BOLD>, [<EM>Holland</EM>], para 43.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>38. In <CASEREF><SOC>Garreton v. Complete Innovations Inc.</SOC><CITE>2016 ONSC 1178</CITE><COURTJUR>Div. Ct</COURTJUR></CASEREF> <BOLD>[<EM>Garreton</EM>],</BOLD> review of the failure of the trial judge to consider whether a termination provision was void and unenforceable for violation of the <EM>ESA</EM> was based on correctness.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Garreton</EM> paras 15&ndash;17.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>39. If necessary to determine, the issue of whether the negotiated terms of employment or the subsequent contract applies is a mixed fact and law question; however the question of consideration is a legal one and the motion judge declined to rule on it, rendering it primarily an error of law.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Holland</EM> para 41.</BOLD></P1></P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><TI><UNDER><EM>Machtinger summarized</EM></UNDER></TI>
<P>40. <BOLD><EM>Machtinger</EM></BOLD> characterizes the common law principle of termination only on reasonable notice as a presumption, rebuttable if the contract of employment clearly specifies some other period of notice, whether expressly or impliedly. However, the decision clarifies that if the parties intended to contract out of the <EM>ESA</EM> and / or did so, the reasonable notice presumption will not be rebutted. Such is the case in this matter.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Machtinger</EM> p. 998, 1001, 1004.</BOLD></P1></P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><TI><UNDER><EM>Minimum Entitlements</EM></UNDER></TI>
<P>41. Contracting out of the minimum termination entitlements under the <EM>Employment Standards Act</EM> renders those provisions void:
<QUOTE><SEC><N>5.</N><SECP>(1) Subject to subsection (2), no employer or agent of an employer and no employee or agent of an employee shall contract out of or waive an employment standard and any such contracting out or waiver is void.</SECP></SEC></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD><EM>Employment Standards Act</EM> 2000, S.O. 2000, c. 41, [<EM>ESA</EM>], s. 5 (1), at Appendix B.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>42. NORR asked Ariss to contract out of his minimum entitlements under the <EM>ESA</EM> respecting termination and severance entitlements in multiple ways, as is evident from the language used in the judgment:
<QUOTE><P>Souter asks Gerstmar to call Ariss and tell him that NORR will not agree to the change from a full-time to a part-time position unless Ariss <BOLD><EM>both</EM></BOLD> resigns from his full-time position <BOLD><EM>and</EM></BOLD> waives his past years' termination and severance entitlement. (emphasis added).</P></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD>Judgment para 57, at ABCO Tab 7, p. 40.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>43. NORR also confirmed the requirement that Ariss had to &ldquo;start fresh&rdquo; if he was going to go part-time and that service entitlements accrual would begin when he started part-time.
<P1><BOLD>Ariss Cross P. 28, Q 178, at ABCO Tab 11, p. 75 and EB Tab 7, p. 208.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>44. Corthorn J. articulated NORR's goal in their requirement for him to resign from his full-time position: &ldquo;to establish an end to Ariss' employment in 2013, breaking his years of continuous service, and beginning new employment on a part-time basis.&rdquo; This demonstrates an intention to contract out of the <EM>ESA</EM> notice of termination entitlements under s. 57. They attempted to create a break in his service when there was none and only provide notice under the <EM>ESA</EM> from the start date of the new contract in 2013.
<P1><BOLD>Judgment paras 93, 94, 96, at ABCO Tab 7, p. 46.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD><EM>ESA</EM>, s. 57 at Appendix B.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>45. A waiver of termination and severance pay for previous years of service has greater consequences upon minimum <EM>ESA</EM> entitlements than the break of service that NORR sought in Ariss' resignation from his full-time position; severance pay flows even in the event of a break in service:
<QUOTE><SEC><N>65.</N><SSEC><N>(2)</N><SSECP>All time spent by the employee in the employer's employ, whether or not continuous and whether or not active, shall be included in determining whether he or she is eligible for severance pay under subsection 64 (1) and in calculating his or her severance pay under subsection (1).</SSECP></SSEC></SEC></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD><EM>ESA</EM>, s. 65 (2), at Appendix B.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>46. By insisting he waive termination and severance pay for previous years of service, NORR was asking Ariss to contract out of the <EM>ESA</EM>. Specifically, NORR intended to contract out of s. 57 regarding notice of termination and s. 65 regarding severance pay. Even if Ariss had resigned in the legal sense in 2013, and had no credit for years of service prior to the sale of business, which was not found to be the case, he would still have an entitlement to severance pay at the time. He was asked to waive it.
<P1><BOLD>Judgment para 93, 96, at ABCO Tab 7, p. 46.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>Ariss Affidavit Exhibit E, at ABCO Tab 12E, p. 90 and EB Tab 1E, p. 24.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>Gerstmar Affidavit para 13, at ABCO Tab 15, p. 146 and EB Tab 3, p. 143.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>Souter Affidavit para 24, at ABCO Tab 14, p. 116 and EB Tab 2, p. 68.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD><EM>ESA</EM> s. 57, 64, 65 at Appendix B.</BOLD></P1></P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><TI><UNDER><EM>Intention to Contract out of Minimum Entitlements</EM></UNDER></TI>
<P>47. &ldquo;If the intention of the parties is to make an unlawful contract, no lawful contractual term can be derived from their intention.&rdquo;
<P1><BOLD><EM>Machtinger</EM> p. 1001.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>48. The Court has the benefit of NORR's evidence that they intended that Ariss' new terms of employment would not include termination and severance pay for years of service prior to July 2013 and that they would not have done the deal to allow him to assume part-time employment in the absence of those terms and a resignation from his full-time position. Effectively, they intended to contract out of the <EM>ESA</EM>. No clause limiting their entitlements to the minimums under the <EM>ESA</EM> can arise in the circumstances.
<P1><BOLD>Gerstmar Affidavit para 13, at ABCO Tab 15, p. 146 and EB Tab 3, p. 143.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>Souter Affidavit para 24, at ABCO Tab 14, p. 116 and EB Tab 2, p. 168.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>Souter Affidavit Exhibit E, at ABCO Tab 14E, p. 122 and EB Tab 2E, p. 98 / Gerstmar Affidavit, Exhibit B, at ABCO Tab 15B, p. 148 and EB Tab 3B, p. 149.</BOLD></P1></P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><TI><UNDER><EM>Contracting out of ESA</EM></UNDER></TI>
<P>49. Not only did the parties intend to contract out of the <EM>ESA</EM>, thus preventing the finding that they are limited to <EM>ESA</EM> minimums only, they did contract out of the <EM>ESA</EM>.</P>
<P>50. &ldquo;In my view, an approach more consistent with the objects of the Act is that, if an employment contract fails to comply with the minimum statutory notice provisions of the Act, then the presumption of reasonable notice will not have been rebutted.&rdquo;
<P1><BOLD>Machtinger p. 1004.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>51. Corthorn J. did not make an express determination about whether the negotiations for part-time work in 2013 or the contract that followed the commencement of that work governed Ariss' employment at the time of his dismissal.
<P1><BOLD>Judgment para 78, at ABCO Tab 7, p. 43.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>52. If the negotiated terms govern, which were determined by July 11, 2013, including the agreement to resign from his full-time position, waive termination and severance pay for previous years of service, and commence <EM>ESA</EM> entitlements as of the start date of part-time work only, then there is a reasonable notice entitlement due to the failure to comply with the minimum statutory provisions of the <EM>ESA</EM>. Ariss met these requirements and confirmed these terms by providing his July 17, 2013 resignation letter.
<P1><BOLD>Souter Affidavit para 20, at ABCO Tab 14, p. 114 and EB Tab 2, p. 66.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>Ariss Affidavit Exhibit E, at ABCO Tab 12E, p. 90 and EB Tab 1E, p. 24.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>53. If the subsequent written contract signed July 31, 2013 governs, then it must capture the negotiated terms. It should be read as providing the minimum notice under the <EM>ESA</EM> from the start date of the contract, which is offside the legislation for failing to recognize previous years of service. It must also be read in the context of the July 17, 2013 letter that Ariss provided, acting upon the negotiated terms, which stipulated that he was resigning from his full-time employment and that termination and severance pay for past years of service would not form part of the terms of his new contract of employment.
<P1><BOLD>Ariss Affidavit Exhibit E, at ABCO Tab 12E, p. 90 and EB Tab 1E, p. 24.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>Souter Affidavit Exhibit I, at ABCO Tab 14I, p. 140 and EB Tab 21, p. 116.</BOLD></P1></P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><TI><UNDER><EM>Consideration</EM></UNDER></TI>
<P>54. Corthorn J. found that she need not determine the issue of consideration for rebutting the reasonable notice entitlement on account of her findings of intention to do so based on the historical termination provision. If the negotiated terms and the terms of the written contract differ, then consideration is relevant.
<P1><BOLD>Judgment paras 80, 81, at ABCO Tab 7, p. 44.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>55. The Respondent's evidence is that all terms of Ariss' part-time work were agreed upon by July 11, 2013, including the agreement to resign from his full-time position. Ariss commenced part-time work on July 15, 2013, in consideration for agreeing to those terms. Acting upon the negotiated terms, Ariss provided his July 17, 2013 resignation letter. It is these terms that governed.
<P1><BOLD>Souter Affidavit para 20, at ABCO Tab 14, p. 114 and EB Tab 2, p. 66.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>Ariss Affidavit para 20, at ABCO Tab 12, p. 80 and EB Tab 1, p. 4.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>Ariss Affidavit Exhibit E, at ABCO Tab 12E, p. 90 and EB Tab 1E, p. 24.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>56. It wasn't until July 23, 2013, after he had been working under those terms of part-time employment, and after providing his July 17, 2013 resignation letter, that Ariss was presented an employment contract with a retroactive start date to July 15, 2013, that stated, &ldquo;Either party may terminate this agreement by providing the minimum notice required under the Employment Standards Act of Ontario.&rdquo; He signed it on July 31, 2013.
<P1><BOLD>Ariss Affidavit Exhibit E, at ABCO Tab 12E, p. 90 and EB Tab 1E, p. 24.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>Ariss Affidavit para 23, 24 at ABCO Tab 12, p. 80, 81 and EB Tab 1, p. 4, 5.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>Ariss Affidavit Exhibit F, at ABCO Tab 12F, p. 92 and EB Tab 1F, p. 26.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>Souter Affidavit Exhibit H, at ABCO Tab 14H, p. 136 and EB Tab 2H, p. 112.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>Souter Affidavit Exhibit I, at ABCO Tab 14I, p. 140 and EB Tab 2I, p. 117.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>Judgment para 68, 69, at ABCO Tab 7, p. 42.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>57. Though we state it is evident the parties contracted out of the <EM>ESA</EM> and relied upon it, if the employment contract subsequently executed on July 31, 2013 is seen on its face to properly limit termination entitlements, it cannot stand for lack of consideration, as the earlier negotiated terms give rise to a reasonable notice entitlement.
<P1><BOLD>Ariss Affidavit para 23, 24 at ABCO Tab 12, p. 80, 81 and EB Tab 1, p. 4, 5.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>Ariss Affidavit Exhibit F, at ABCO Tab 12F, p. 92 and EB Tab 1F, p. 26.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>Souter Affidavit Exhibit I, at ABCO Tab 14I, p. 140 and EB Tab 2I, p. 116.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>58. Such was the case in <BOLD><EM>Holland</EM>,</BOLD> where a contract purporting to limit termination entitlements to the minimums under the <EM>ESA</EM> was presented to an employee after he had started working on the basis of negotiated terms, including an entitlement to reasonable notice of the termination of his employment. The subsequent contract could not limit entitlements to the minimums under the <EM>ESA</EM> for lack of consideration:
<QUOTE><P>Without fresh consideration, the Employment Agreement could not displace the implied term of reasonable notice contained in the Offer Letter. The result is that the appellant was entitled to reasonable notice of termination at common law.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD><EM>Holland</EM> at para 15.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>59. To the extent that the subsequent contract in isolation is seen to limit to the minimum entitlements under the <EM>ESA</EM> and not contract out of those entitlements, which we deny, then there was no consideration for agreeing to less favourable terms of employment that limited entitlements upon dismissal to those under the <EM>ESA</EM>. A reasonable notice entitlement flows.
<P1><BOLD>Souter Affidavit Exhibit I, at ABCO Tab 14I, p. 140 and EB Tab 2I, p. 116.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>Ariss Affidavit Exhibit F, at ABCO Tab 12F, p. 92 and EB Tab 1F, p. 26.</BOLD></P1></P>
<BLOCK5><TI><EM>Provided less than ESA minimums upon dismissal</EM></TI>
<P>60. Consistent with their stated intentions and actions, NORR provided less than Ariss' minimum entitlements when they terminated his employment without cause in January 2016.
<P1><BOLD>Judgment para 11, 117, at ABCO Tab 7, p. 29, 49.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>61. Upon Ariss' dismissal, NORR believed he had only a two week notice of termination entitlement&mdash;consistent with counting years of service only from July 2013 to January 2016 and waiving termination pay for previous years of service. They believed he had no severance entitlement&mdash;consistent with a waiver of severance pay for years of service prior to July 2013. NORR acted upon the negotiated terms.
<P1><BOLD>Judgment para 13, at ABCO Tab 7, p. 30.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD><EM>ESA</EM>, s. 57, 64, 65, at Appendix B.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>62. NORR took the position upon dismissal that Ariss' years of continuous service ended in 2013 and that he had no severance entitlement, but then in turn obtained the benefit as if they had drafted a valid termination provision that limited to <EM>ESA</EM> only. It was not their intention to provide him his actual <EM>ESA</EM> entitlement and they did not so do.
<P1><BOLD>Judgment para 13, 41, 93, 117, at ABCO Tab 7, p. 30, 36, 46, 49.</BOLD></P1></P></BLOCK5></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><TI><UNDER><EM>Error in Finding Reasonable Notice Presumption Rebutted</EM></UNDER></TI>
<P>63. While the intention of NORR may have been to rebut the reasonable notice presumption, they cannot succeed in doing so where they intended to contract out of the provisions of the <EM>ESA</EM> respecting termination and severance pay, did so, and then relied on that contracting out:
<QUOTE><P>In argument, the respondent accepted that the attempt to contract out of the provisions of the Act was &ldquo;null and void&rdquo;, but argued that the documents should be considered as evidence &ldquo;that contracts were entered into which expressed clearly the intention of the parties with respect to notice of termination.&rdquo; I cannot accept this argument.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD>Machtinger p. 928.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>64. This is where Corthorn J. erred. She looked at the intention of the parties to provide minimum entitlements under the <EM>ESA</EM> by reviewing the &ldquo;historical termination provision&rdquo; in Ariss' earlier contracts with NORR in 2002 and 2006 rather than the terms agreed upon in his negotiations for part-time work in 2013. NORR did not ultimately use the &ldquo;historical termination provision&rdquo; in 2013, but chose different language that did not comply with minimum entitlements.
<P1><BOLD>Judgment para 78, 79, 80, 81, at ABCO Tab 7, p. 43, 44.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>Ariss Affidavit Exhibit F, at ABCO Tab 12F, p. 92 and EB Tab 1F, p. 26.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>Souter Affidavit Exhibit I, at ABCO Tab 14I, p. 140 and EB Tab 2I, p. 116.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>65. To allow the consequence to NORR for contracting out of the <EM>ESA</EM> to be payment of the <EM>ESA</EM> creates troubling policy issues:
<QUOTE><P>If the only sanction which employers potentially face for failure to comply with the minimum notice periods prescribed by the Act is an order that they minimally comply with the Act, employers will have little incentive to make contracts with their employees that comply with the Act.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD>Machtinger p. 1004.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>66. It was open to NORR to negotiate terms of part-time employment that limited to the <EM>ESA</EM>, by simply inserting the same &ldquo;historical termination provision&rdquo; that had been in every other contract they had with Ariss into a part-time contract, but they did not do so. They insisted on a resignation from full-time employment and a waiver of termination and severance pay for previous years of service, and a start date for <EM>ESA</EM> entitlements as of the start date of the part-time contract. These terms were offside the legislation and cannot govern:
<QUOTE><P>An employer who wishes to guard against being called upon to give any more notice or severance pay than legislation demands can readily draw a contractual clause which, in effect, converts the statutory floor into a ceiling. But here the employer has authored a contractual term which simply fails to comply with the law. In such circumstances, it is not evident why the employee should be placed in a worse position than if the contract had said nothing at all about notice of termination.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD>Machtinger p. 1005.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>67. If employers are able to contract out of the <EM>ESA</EM> with minimal consequence, mistakenly or not, the impact on employees is substantial:
<QUOTE><P>Employers can rely on the fact that many employees will not challenge contractual notice provisions which are in fact contrary to employment standards legislation. Employers such as the present respondent can contract with their employees for notice periods below the statutory minimum, knowing that only those individual employees who take legal action after they are dismissed will in fact receive the protection of the minimum statutory notice provisions.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD>Machtinger p. 1004.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>68. This was the position that Ariss found himself in. Corthorn J. acknowledged as much in her Costs endorsement:
<QUOTE><P>NORR's position is that the approach taken at the time of Ariss' termination was based on its &ldquo;understanding of the duration of Mr. Ariss' employment at the time.&rdquo; NORR's approach was found to be in error. In the context of the determination of costs, NORR cannot rely on an erroneous approach in that regard. It is specifically because of NORR's approach that Ariss was required to pursue the matter as far as he did.</P>
<P>Had Ariss not pursued the matter, he would have been denied the compensation to which he was entitled after a career of several decades at NORR and its predecessor company.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD>Costs endorsement, para 20, 21, at ABCO Tab 8, p. 55.</BOLD></P1></P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><TI><UNDER><EM>Machtinger Applied</EM></UNDER></TI>
<P>69. The Divisional Court in 2016 confirmed the approach in <BOLD><EM>Machtinger</EM></BOLD> that if s. 5 of the <EM>ESA</EM> (s. 3 at the time <BOLD><EM>Machtinger</EM></BOLD> was decided) is breached with respect to entitlements upon dismissal, then reasonable notice applies:
<QUOTE><P>If the termination provision is not onside with notice provisions and severance provisions (if applicable) of the Act at the outset, then it is void and unenforceable. Potential violation in the future is sufficient. As Low J. states, &ldquo;It is not that difficult to draft a clause that complies completely with the Act, no matter the circumstance.&rdquo;</P></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD><EM>Garreton</EM> at paras 18, 27, 28.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>70. Accordingly, NORR did not rebut the reasonable notice presumption and Ariss has a 22 month reasonable notice entitlement.</P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><TI><UNDER><EM>Costs</EM></UNDER></TI>
<P>71. As the Respondent's Rule 49 Offer was greater than the amount awarded in the Judgment, Corthorn J. ordered the Respondent to pay partial indemnity to the Appellant to the date of their offer to settle and ordered the Appellant to pay to the Respondent partial indemnity costs thereafter. The net result was an Order for the Appellant to pay $20,390 to the Respondent.
<P1><BOLD>Costs endorsement para 24, 25, 26, at ABCO Tab 8, p. 55.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>Defendant's Offer to Settle, dated November 9, 2016, [Defendant's Offer to Settle] at ABCO Tab 17, p. 162 and EB Tab 6, p. 174.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>Bill of Costs of the Defendant, dated April 6, 2018, at ABCO Tab 18, p. 173 and EB Tab 8, p. 248.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>Bill of Costs of the Plaintiff, dated April 26, 2018, [Plaintiff's Bill of Costs], at ABCO Tab 19, p. 177 and EB Tab 9, p. 260.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>72. If the Appellant is successful in the appeal and cross appeal such that the award in total is greater than his own Offer to Settle, then no costs should flow to the Respondent. Instead, the Appellant should be entitled to partial indemnity costs to the date of his offer on October 12, 2016, which is $7,652.49, and substantial indemnity costs thereafter in the amount of $46,995.40, for a total costs award in the first instance pursuant to Rule 49.10(1) of $54,647.89.
<P1><BOLD>Plaintiff's Offer to Settle, dated October 12, 2016, [Plaintiff's Offer to Settle] at ABCO Tab 16, p. 159 and EB Tab 5, p. 171.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>Plaintiff's Bill of Costs, at ABCO Tab 19, p. 175 and EB Tab 9, p. 258.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>Costs Outline of the Plaintiff, dated April 26, 2018, at ABCO Tab 20, p. 181 and EB Tab 10, p. 264.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD><EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM> R.R.O. 1990, Reg. 194 [<EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM>], R. 49.10 (1), at Appendix B.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>73. If the Appellant is successful in the appeal and cross appeal such that that the award in total is less than his own Offer to Settle, but more than the Respondent's Offer, no costs should flow to the Respondent. Instead, the Appellant should be entitled to partial indemnity costs throughout the proceedings in the first instance in the amount of $38,982.76.
<P1><BOLD>Plaintiff's Offer to Settle, at ABCO Tab 16, p. 159 and EB Tab 5, p. 171.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD><EM>Courts of Justice Act</EM>, R.S.O. 1990, Chapter C.43, s. 131 (1), at Appendix B.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>Defendant's Offer to Settle, at ABCO Tab 17, p. 162 and EB Tab 6, p. 174.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD><EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM>, Rule 57.01, at Appendix B.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>74. To be clear, the Appellant does not state that the motion judge erred in her Costs endorsement based on her determination in the Judgment, but rather that costs in the first instance should be varied if the Appellant is successful upon the appeal and cross appeal. We agree with the motion judge that Rule 49 of the <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM> should govern costs at first instance, if applicable.</P></BLOCK4></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="V">PART V&mdash;RELIEF SOUGHT</TI>
<P>75. The remedy that flows is a 22 month reasonable notice entitlement for the Appellant, which Corthorn J. has determined would be the appropriate length had there been such an entitlement, along with costs to follow the event, both in first instance and at the appeal.</P>
<P>76. The Appellant seeks an order
<P1>a) Declaring that he has an entitlement to a 22 month reasonable notice period;</P1>
<P1>b) For the costs of this appeal on a substantial indemnity basis;</P1>
<P1>c) For leave to appeal the costs endorsement in first instance, dated May 22, 2018;</P1>
<P1>d) For its costs in the first instance in accordance with Rule 49.10 (1), in the amount of $54,647.89;</P1>
<P1>e) That it does not owe costs to the Respondent in connection with the costs endorsement in first instance.</P1></P>
<P><BOLD>ALL OF WHICH IS RESPECTFULLY SUBMITTED.</BOLD></P>
<P>Dated at Ottawa, Ontario, June 14, 2018.</P>
<P>&ellip35; Alayna Miller</P>
<P>Solicitor for the Appellant, John David Ariss</P></BLOCK2></BLOCK1>
