<BLOCK0><TI>FACTUM OF THE DEFENDANT (RESPONDENT, APPELLANT IN CROSS APPEAL)</TI>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="I">PART I&mdash;OVERVIEW</TI>
<P>1. This appeal and cross-appeal arise from a summary judgment motion brought by the plaintiff, John David Ariss <BOLD>(&ldquo;Ariss&rdquo;)</BOLD> against his former employer, NORR Limited Architects and Engineers <BOLD>(&ldquo;NORR&rdquo;)</BOLD> for determination of his claim of wrongful dismissal.</P>
<P>2. The termination provision in Ariss' contract of employment with NORR limits Ariss' entitlements to the minimums specified by the <EM>Employment Standards Act, 2002</EM>, S.O. 2000, c. 41 (the <BOLD>&ldquo;ESA&rdquo;</BOLD>). The motion judge held, among other things, that the termination provision is sufficiently clear and unambiguous, and rebuts the common law presumption of reasonable notice of the termination of his employment.</P>
<P>3. The motion judge correctly applied the legal principles outlined in <CASEREF><SOC>Machtinger v. HOJ Industries Ltd.</SOC><CITE>[1992] 1 S.C.R. 986</CITE></CASEREF> (&ldquo;<EM>Machtinger</EM>&rdquo;), which provide that the presumption of common law reasonable notice upon termination of employment is rebuttable if the contract of employment clearly specifies some other period of notice that complies with the ESA. The motion judge's findings are entitled to deference and can only be interfered with in cases of palpable and overriding error.</P>
<P>4. The motion judge's decision is proper for the following reasons:
<P1>(a) Ariss' written employment contract clearly limits his entitlements upon termination of his employment to the ESA minimums;</P1>
<P1>(b) Ariss' written employment contract does not contain language that purports to waive any entitlements to employment standards protected by the ESA;</P1>
<P1>(c) the enforceability of a termination clause depends only on the wording of the clause itself;</P1>
<P1>(d) the motion judge made a finding of fact that Ariss fully understood, at all times during his employment with NORR, that his entitlements on the termination of his employment would be in accordance with the ESA;</P1>
<P1>(e) the motion judge considered Ariss and NORR's agreement that Ariss would resign in 2013 upon transitioning to part-time hours and held that there was no interruption in the continuity of Ariss' employment with NORR, and that the resignation was not successful; and</P1>
<P1>(f) the alleged &ldquo;waiver&rdquo; of Ariss' termination and severance pay for his past years' of service was a result of Ariss' purported resignation, and, accordingly, was also not successful and has no effect.</P1></P>
<P>5. Ariss has not demonstrated or alleged palpable and overriding error in the motion judge's decision. NORR submits that Ariss' appeal should be denied.</P>
<P>6. If this Court finds that the motion judge erred in finding that Ariss was limited to the minimum ESA entitlements, then NORR cross-appeals and submits that the motion judge erred by failing to consider the issue of mitigation. Ariss has a duty to take all reasonable steps to mitigate his damages and reduce the amount payable by NORR, but his mitigation efforts are minimal and insufficient. In such circumstances, reasonable notice becomes a triable issue that is not appropriate for summary judgment. The motion judge's decision not to consider the issue of mitigation is reviewable on a correctness standard. It is appropriate for this Court to interfere with the motion judge's decision not to consider Ariss' failure to mitigate.</P></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="II">PART II&mdash;SUMMARY OF FACTS</TI>
<BLOCK2><TI><EM>Ariss' Employment With NORR</EM></TI>
<P>7. Ariss was hired as an architect by a company located in Kingston, Ontario in 1986. Upon the sale of the company's business assets to NORR in November 2002, Ariss was hired by NORR as a full-time Senior Architect.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Ariss v NORR Limited Architects and Engineers</SOC><CITE>2018 ONSC 620</CITE></CASEREF> <BOLD>[Judgment],</BOLD> paras 4-5, at Ariss' Appeal Book and Compendium <BOLD>[ABCO],</BOLD> Tab 7, p 29.</P1>
<P1>Affidavit of Jacqui Souter sworn March 10, 2017 <BOLD>[Souter Affidavit],</BOLD> paras 3-4, at NORR's Compendium <BOLD>[Compendium],</BOLD> Tab 2, p 43.</P1></P>
<P>8. Ariss' contract with NORR (the <BOLD>&ldquo;2002 Contract&rdquo;</BOLD>) contains terms which limit Ariss' termination entitlements to ESA minimums.
<P1>Affidavit of John David Ariss sworn January 9, 2017 <BOLD>[Ariss Affidavit],</BOLD> Exhibit C, at Compendium, Tab 1-C, pp 14&ndash;16.</P1>
<P1>Souter Affidavit, para 8, at Compendium, Tab 2, pp 44-45.</P1>
<P1>Souter Affidavit, Exhibit A, at Compendium, Tab 2-A, pp 56&ndash;67.</P1>
<P1>Cross-Examination of John David Ariss held April 24, 2017 <BOLD>[Ariss Cross-Examination],</BOLD> p 16-17, Q 108, at Compendium, Tab 5, pp 130-131.</P1></P>
<P>9. In 2006, Ariss requested and receive an increase in hours and signed an amendment to his contract to that effect (the <BOLD>&ldquo;2006 Amendment&rdquo;</BOLD>). As in the 2002 Contract, the 2006 Amendment contains terms which limited Ariss' termination entitlements to ESA minimums. The termination provision states that notice will be provided &ldquo;in accordance with the Ontario Employment Standards Act&rdquo; and includes a chart that specifically lists the notice period for each period of employment.
<P1>Souter Affidavit, paras 9&ndash;11, at Compendium, Tab 2, p 45.</P1>
<P1>Ariss Affidavit, Exhibit D, at Compendium, Tab 1-D, pp 18&ndash;22.</P1></P>
<P>10. On cross-examination, Ariss confirmed that he had read the terms when he signed the 2006 Amendment and that he understood at that time that it limited his termination entitlements to ESA minimums.
<P1>Ariss Cross-Examination, pp 19-20, Q 121&ndash;127, at Compendium, Tab 5, pp 133-134.</P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><EM>Transition to Part-Time Hours</EM></TI>
<P>11. In February 2013, Ariss approached NORR with a desire to transition to part-time hours. On May 31, 2013, Ariss made a written request to NORR to transition to part-time hours and proposed revisions to his contract of employment with NORR.
<P1>Souter Affidavit, paras 13-14 at Compendium, Tab 2, p 46.</P1>
<P1>Souter Affidavit, Exhibit C, at Compendium, Tab 2-C, p 69&ndash;71.</P1></P>
<P>12. NORR considered Ariss' proposal and raised a number of concerns. The primary concern was that Ariss would not be effective in a part-time role. As a Senior Architect, Ariss was responsible for managing projects and communicating with clients. In NORR's view, it would be difficult to satisfy NORR's demanding clients when working part-time hours. Furthermore, NORR had no one to take over Ariss' responsibilities in the office on days when he was not working. Another concern was that the terms of Ariss' proposal were too similar to what full-time NORR employees received.
<P1>Souter Affidavit, paras 16 and 19, at Compendium, Tab 2, pp 47-48.</P1>
<P1>Souter Affidavit, Exhibit D, at Compendium, Tab 2 -D, pp 73-74.</P1>
<P1>Affidavit of Brian Gerstmar sworn March 10, 2017 <BOLD>[Gerstmar Affidavit],</BOLD> paras 3, 5, and 10, at Compendium, Tab 3, pp 108, 110.</P1>
<P1>Gerstmar Affidavit, Exhibit C, at Compendium, Tab 3-C, pp 113&ndash;116.</P1></P>
<P>13. However, NORR thought that Ariss could still make a valuable contribution to its Kingston office. To satisfy the concerns and priorities of both parties, Ariss and NORR agreed that Ariss would resign. Ariss' resignation would mean that his past years of service would not be counted in future calculations of his entitlements should his employment be terminated. However, the motion judge found that the parties were not successful in the attempt to effect a resignation.
<P1>Souter Affidavit, para 17, at Compendium, Tab 2, p 47.</P1>
<P1>Gerstmar Affidavit, paras 10&ndash;13, at Compendium, Tab 3, p .</P1>
<P1>Gerstmar Affidavit, Exhibit C, at Compendium, Tab 3-C, p 110.</P1>
<P1>Judgment, paras 93&ndash;96, at ABCO, Tab 7, p 46.</P1></P>
<P>14. Though Ariss submitted a resignation letter to NORR, there was no break in his employment with NORR. The motion judge made a finding of fact that there was no interruption in the continuity of Ariss' employment, and therefore no effective resignation or waiver of his termination or severance entitlements under the ESA for his past years of service.
<P1>Ariss Affidavit, Exhibit E, at Compendium, Tab 1-E, p 24.</P1>
<P1>Judgment, paras 93&ndash;96, at ABCO, Tab 7, p 46.</P1></P>
<P>15. NORR and Ariss agreed on the compensation terms of his transition to part-time hours by July 11, 2013, and Ariss was presented with a written document to that effect on July 23, 2013, which he signed on July 31, 2013 (the <BOLD>&ldquo;2013 Amendment&rdquo;</BOLD>).
<P1>Souter Affidavit, Exhibit D, at Compendium, Tab 2-D, pp 73-74.</P1>
<P1>Souter Affidavit, Exhibit E, at Compendium, Tab 2-E, pp 76&ndash;82.</P1>
<P1>Gerstmar Affidavit, para 11, at Compendium, Tab 3, p 110.</P1>
<P1>Gerstmar Affidavit, Exhibit C, at Compendium, Tab 3-C, pp 113&ndash;116.</P1>
<P1>Souter Affidavit, paras 25-26, at Compendium, Tab 2, p 50.</P1>
<P1>Souter Affidavit, Exhibit H, at Compendium, Tab 2-H, pp 84&ndash;87.</P1>
<P1>Souter Affidavit, Exhibit I, at Compendium, Tab 2-I, pp 89-90.</P1></P>
<P>16. The termination provision in the 2013 Amendment is consistent with the termination provisions in the 2002 Contract and 2006 Amendment, and states; &ldquo;Either party may terminate this agreement by providing the minimum notice required under the Employment Standards Act of Ontario.&rdquo; The termination provision complies with the ESA and does not waive any of Ariss' entitlements to termination or severance pay under the ESA.
<P1>Souter Affidavit, Exhibit I, at Compendium, Tab 2-I, pp 89-90.</P1>
<P1>Judgment, paras 75 and 77, at ABCO, Tab 7, p 43.</P1></P>
<P>17. The 2013 Amendment also includes the following paragraph:
<QUOTE><P>This offer of employment contains all relevant and material terms of your employment with NORR. If you believe that any oral commitments have been made to you that are not contained herein, you must bring them to the attention of the undersigned representative of NORR without delay. Any such commitments are neither valid nor binding unless confirmed and documented by the undersigned representative of NORR.</P></QUOTE>
<P1>Souter Affidavit, Exhibit I, at Compendium, Tab 2-I, pp 89-90.</P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><EM>Termination of Ariss' Employment</EM></TI>
<P>18. NORR's Kingston office was primarily focused on correctional and government service projects. In late 2012 or early 2013, NORR lost a standing service agreement that had allowed it to bid or participate in government projects. NORR's efforts to resolve this issue in 20 14 and 2015 were unsuccessful. This had a significant negative effect on the financial health of NORR's Kingston office and it created a severe shortage of work. For these reasons, NORR notified Ariss on January 26, 20 16 that his employment with NORR would be terminated effective February 19, 2016.
<P1>Souter Affidavit, paras 28&ndash;30, at Compendium, Tab 2, p 51.</P1>
<P1>Gerstmar Affidavit, para 15, at Compendium, Tab 3, p 111.</P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><EM>Ariss' Failure to Mitigate</EM></TI>
<P>19. Ariss has not taken reasonable steps to find alternate employment since his dismissal. Ariss has made minimal efforts to find a new position in Kingston (the city where he resides). Ariss has not sought the assistance of a recruitment agency or taken courses to update his skills&mdash;for example, by learning basic architecture software, which he knows would make him more marketable.
<P1>Ariss Cross-Examination, pp 60&ndash;64, Q 379&ndash;401, at Compendium, Tab 5, pp 157&ndash;161.</P1></P>
<P>20. Furthermore, Ariss has almost exclusively searched for jobs in Kingston, which is a very small architecture market. Ariss has acknowledged that by December 20 16, he knew it was unlikely that he would get a job in Kingston as an architect, yet he did not expand his search.
<P1>Ariss Cross-Examination, p 52, Q 318; p 57, Q 354&ndash;359; p 61, Q 385, at Compendium, Tab 5, pp 153-154, 158.</P1>
<P1>Souter Affidavit, para 37, at Compendium, Tab 2, p 53.</P1></P>
<P>21. NORR has shown that suitable job opportunities have been available to Ariss in Ottawa. Ariss has admitted to seeing job opportunities that he is likely qualified for, but the opportunities are located outside of Kingston and Ariss has not applied for any of the opportunities. In addition, Ariss did not broaden his search beyond architectural positions.
<P1>Souter Affidavit, para 38, at Compendium, Tab 2, p 54.</P1>
<P1>Souter Affidavit, Exhibit L, at Compendium, Tab 2-L, pp 92&ndash;106.</P1>
<P1>Ariss Cross-Examination, pp 57-58, Q 361&ndash;364; pp 64&ndash;66, Q 402&ndash;418, at Compendium, Tab 5, pp 154-155, 161&ndash;163.</P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><EM>The Motion Judge's Decision</EM></TI>
<P>22. Ariss commenced an action against NORR for wrongful dismissal and moved for summary judgment. The motion judge concluded that the issues were capable of determination on the motion and a trial was not required. Success on the motion was divided. The motion judge applied the principles outlined by the Supreme Court of Canada in <EM>Machtinger</EM>, and held, among other things, that Ariss' entitlement to notice upon the termination of his employment was restricted to the provisions of the ESA because of the termination provision in his written employment agreement.
<P1>Judgment, para 82, at ABCO, Tab 7, p 44.</P1></P></BLOCK2></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="III">PART III&mdash;POSITION ON ISSUES</TI>
<BLOCK2><TI>APPEAL ISSUE ONE: The motion judge properly held that Ariss is entitled to notice of termination of his employment in accordance with the ESA.</TI>
<BLOCK3><N>A.</N><TI>THE STANDARD OF REVIEW</TI>
<P>23. The interpretation of a contractual clause is entitled to deference from an appellate court and should not be overturned absent palpable and overriding error, unless an error of law can be extricated from the motion judge's interpretation of the clause.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Creston Moly Corp v Sattva Capital Corp</SOC><CITE>2014 SCC 53</CITE><PARANUM>50, 52</PARANUM></CASEREF></P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Wood v Fred Deeley</SOC><CITE>2017 ONCA 158</CITE><PARANUM>43</PARANUM></CASEREF> <BOLD>[<EM>Wood</EM>]</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>24. Palpable and overriding error means &ldquo;clearly wrong&rdquo;, &ldquo;unreasonable&rdquo; and &ldquo;not reasonably supported by the evidence&rdquo;.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Garreton v Complete Innovations Inc</SOC><CITE>2016 ONSC 1178</CITE><COURTJUR>Div Ct</COURTJUR></CASEREF>, at para 13 <BOLD>[<EM>Garreton</EM>]</BOLD>, citing <CASEREF><SOC>L (H) v Canada (Attorney General)</SOC><CITE>[2005] 1 SCR 401</CITE><PARANUM>110</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P1></P>
<P>25. Ariss refers to <EM>Garreton</EM> to argue that the correctness standard is applicable to the issues raised in this appeal. In <EM>Garreton</EM>, the trial judge held that it was not necessary to determine whether the employment agreement was unenforceable and whether the termination clause was void from the outset. The appellate court found that the trial judge erred in law in failing to deal with the issue of whether the employment agreement, and specifically the termination clause, was void and unenforceable. The court applied a correctness standard.
<P1><EM>Garreton</EM>, <EM>supra</EM> para 24, at paras 14&ndash;17.</P1></P>
<P>26. <EM>Garreton</EM> is distinguishable from Ariss' appeal. In Ariss' case, the motion judge did not fail to consider the enforceability of the termination provision. Instead, the motion judge specifically considered the issue and found that the termination provision is enforceable and rebuts the presumption of common law reasonable notice of the termination of Ariss' employment.
<P1>Judgment, paras 73&ndash;82, at ABCO, Tab 7, p 43-44.</P1></P>
<P>27. NORR submits that there is no extricable legal error in the motion judge's analysis and the standard of review is palpable and overriding error.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>B.</N><TI>THE MOTION JUDGE'S APPLICATION OF <EM>MACHTINGER</EM></TI>
<P>28. The motion judge properly held that Ariss is entitled to notice of termination in accordance with the ESA. The motion judge correctly applied the legal principles out lined in <EM>Machtinger</EM>.</P>
<P>29. <EM>Machtinger</EM> explains that the common law principle of termination only on reasonable notice is a presumption, and is rebuttable if the contract of employment clearly specifies some other period of notice, whether expressly or impliedly. However, if an employment contract fails to comply with the minimum statutory provisions of the ESA, then that portion of the contract will be null and void, and the presumption of reasonable notice will not have been rebutted.
<P1><EM>Machtinger</EM>, <EM>supra</EM> para 3, at paras 20, 26, 34.</P1></P>
<P>30. The motion judge stated that in the 2002 Contract and 2006 Amendment, the termination and severance provisions referred only to the ESA. The motion judge properly held that the language used in the termination provision is clear and unambiguous in rebutting the common law presumption of reasonable notice. Ariss has not alleged that the motion judge erred in this determination.
<P1>Judgment, paras 28, 46, 69, 74, and 77, at ABCO, Tab 7, pp 34, 37, 42, 43.</P1></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><EM>Ariss Did Not Waive His Past Years' Termination and Severance Pay</EM></TI>
<P>31. Despite the discussions between the parties when negotiating Ariss' transition to part-time hours, or the language in the emails or in Ariss' purported resignation letter, the motion judge found that:
<P1>(a) NORR was not successful in establishing an end to Ariss' employment, breaking his years of continuous service, or beginning new employment on a part-time basis;</P1>
<P1>(b) Ariss did not resign; and</P1>
<P1>(c) Ariss' service was continuous from 1986 to 2016 with no interruption.
<P2>Judgment, para 93&ndash;96, at ABCO, Tab 7, p 46.</P2></P1></P>
<P>32. These findings are grounded in the evidence and this Court cannot interfere in the absence of palpable and overriding error. No such error has been demonstrated.</P>
<P>33. The motion judge properly found that the events in 2013 were an amendment to the terms of Ariss' employment with NORR. The events in 2013 are similar to the 2006 Amendment, where Ariss increased his weekly hours and modified his compensation and benefits accordingly. After transitioning to part-time hours in 2013, Ariss performed the same role as when he worked full-time hours. It was only the number of weekly hours, compensation, and benefits that were modified. The modifications were outlined in the 2013 Amendment.
<P1>Judgment, para 95, at ABCO, Tab 7, p 46.</P1></P>
<P>34. Even if the intention of a formal resignation and resulting waiver of past years' termination and severance pay was clear, the requested resignation and waiver has no effect and cannot be relied upon. The motion judge correctly referred to <CASEREF><SOC>Riskie v. Sony Canada Ltd.</SOC><CITE>2015 ONSC 5859</CITE></CASEREF> (&ldquo;<EM>Riskie</EM>&rdquo;), to explain that, even if NORR intended that Ariss resign from his employment with NORR, such request would be &ldquo;an entirely artificial attempt to create an interruption in employment when in fact there was none.&rdquo; The motion judge in <EM>Riskie</EM> held that the formal resignation of an employee, who was transitioning from an employment contract of indefinite duration to a fixed-term contract, was a &ldquo;red herring&rdquo; and had &ldquo;no practical effect even if the intention was clear enough&rdquo;.
<P1>Judgment, para 95, at ABCO, Tab 7, p 46.</P1>
<P1><EM>Riskie</EM>, at paras 27, 54.</P1></P>
<BLOCK4><TI><EM>The Terms of Ariss' Contract of Employment</EM></TI>
<P>35. Given that Ariss' years of continuous service were not interrupted in 2013, the motion judge properly found that the terms of employment to which Ariss was asked to agree in 2013 were no different than the terms to which he had agreed in both 2002 and 2006. These terms include the termination provision, which the motion judge found to be clear and unambiguous in rebutting the common law presumption. The termination provision complied with the ESA and did not waive any of Ariss' entitlements to termination or severance pay under the ESA.
<P1>Judgment, paras 74, 77, at ABCO, Tab 7, p 43.</P1></P>
<P>36. Whether or not the 2013 Amendment used the same language for the termination provision as the 2002 Contract and 2006 Amendment is not material. The termination provision in the 2013 Amendment is consistent with the historical termination provisions, and is sufficiently clear and unambiguous to rebut the common law presumption. The provision states: &ldquo;Either party may terminate this agreement by providing the minimum notice required under the <EM>Employment Standards Act of Ontario</EM>.&rdquo;
<P1>Souter Affidavit, Exhibit I, at Compendium, Tab 2-I, pp 89-90.</P1></P>
<P>37. <EM>Machtinger</EM> held that an employment contract can &ldquo;referentially incorporate the minimum notice periods set out in the Act&rdquo; and that this would be &ldquo;sufficient to displace the presumption&rdquo; of a common law reasonable notice period. The termination provision in the 2013 Amendment explicitly directs Ariss to the ESA and complies with the ESA's minimum entitlements. Further, the 20 13 Amendment states that any other terms are &ldquo;neither valid nor binding unless confirmed and documented&rdquo; by NORR. No additional terms were documented. The motion judge did not err in the interpretation of the termination provision or in holding that Ariss was only entitled to notice of termination in accordance with the ESA.
<P1><EM>Machtinger</EM>, <EM>supra</EM> para 3, at para 35.</P1>
<P1><EM>ESA</EM>, <EM>supra</EM> para 2, at s 57.</P1></P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><TI><EM>Ariss Understood That Termination Entitlements Were Limited to ESA Minimums</EM></TI>
<P>38. Additionally, the motion judge drew an inference and found:
<QUOTE><P>in 2013, when negotiating the terms of his contract for casual employment, Ariss understood that the termination provision in his contract of employment restricted his entitlement to notice and severance pay pursuant to the ESA. It is clear from the contents of Ariss' email in 2013, leading up to the letter signed on July 14, 2013, that he appreciated that the historical termination provision, based on the ESA, continued to apply. I find that Ariss fully understood, both when working full-time and when working part-time, that his entitlements on termination would be in accordance with the ESA.</P></QUOTE>
<P1>Judgment, para 78, at ABCO, Tab 7, p 43.</P1></P>
<P>39. This finding is entitled to deference.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Housen v Nikolaisen</SOC><CITE>2002 SCC 33</CITE></CASEREF> [<EM>Housen</EM>], at para 25.</P1></P>
<P>40. It was clear to the parties, and on the face of the 2002 Contract, the 2006 Amendment, and the 2013 Amendment, that throughout Ariss' employment with NORR, his entitlements upon termination were limited to the ESA minimums.</P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><TI><EM>NORR's Actions on Ariss' Dismissal Are Not Relevant</EM></TI>
<P>41. The enforceability of a termination clause depends only on the wording of the clause itself. In <EM>Wood</EM>, the employer conceded that it paid the employee less than she was entitled under the ESA, but the Court of Appeal held that what the employer may have paid the employee voluntarily on termination had no bearing on whether the termination clause itself is enforceable. The only relevant factor was what the termination clause required the employer to pay the employee.
<P1><EM>Wood</EM>, <EM>supra</EM> para 23, at paras 43&ndash;48, 60.</P1></P>
<P>42. Similarly, whether NORR provided Ariss with more or less than the amount required by the ESA or the termination provision is not relevant to whether or not the termination provision is enforceable.</P></BLOCK4></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>C.</N><TI>THE ISSUE OF CONSIDERATION IS NOT RELEVANT</TI>
<P>43. The motion judge correctly held that the issue of consideration is not relevant to the determination of whether Ariss contracted out of common law reasonable notice. The termination provision sufficiently rebutted the presumption of common law reasonable notice, remained unchanged throughout Ariss' continuous employment with NORR, and Ariss clearly understood that it continued to apply following his transition to part-time hours.
<P1>Judgment, para 81, at ABCO, Tab 7, p 44.</P1></P>
<P>44. If this Court finds that the motion judge erred in failing to address consideration, which is denied, NORR submits that there was good consideration for the 2013 Amendment in NORR agreeing to transition Ariss to part-time hours and increase his hourly rate of pay.</P>
<P>45. It was Ariss who sought to make modifications to his contract of employment with NORR by transitioning to part-time hours. NORR's uncontradicted evidence is that it lost contracts for a number of government standing service agreements in late 2012 or early 2013. NORR was unsuccessful in resolving those losses, and sought to be cautious about allowing Ariss to transition to part-time hours. NORR was under no obligation to accommodate Ariss' request. The 2013 Amendment outlined the terms by which NORR agreed to allow that change.
<P1>Judgment, para 91-92, at ABCO, Tab 7, p 45.</P1></P>
<P>46. Though Ariss began working part-time hours on July 15, 2013, he was employed by NORR pursuant to the terms of the 2002 Contract and 2006 Amendment unless and until the parties agreed to modified terms. Ariss could either agree to the 2013 Amendment, remain employed with NORR in accordance with the terms of his full-time position, or resign completely and cease his employment with NORR. Ariss chose to agree to the 2013 Amendment.</P>
<P>47. Further, the parties had agreed to the terms of the 2013 Amendment by July 11, 2013. The terms did not change after Ariss began working part-time hours on July 15, 2013. Signing an employment agreement shortly after beginning work does not render that agreement void.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Wallace v Toronto Dominion Bank</SOC><YEAR>1983</YEAR><CITE>41 OR (2d) 161</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>145 DLR (3d) 431</CITE></CORRELAT><COURTJUR>Ont CA</COURTJUR></CASEREF>, at para 57.</P1></P>
<P>48. The case relied upon by Ariss, <CASEREF><SOC>Holland v. Hostopia Inc.</SOC><CITE>2015 ONCA 762</CITE></CASEREF>, (&ldquo;<EM>Holland</EM>&rdquo;) is distinguishable. In <EM>Holland</EM>, the employee accepted an offer of employment with an implied term that the employee was entitled to reasonable notice prior to the termination of his employment. Nine months after the employee began working, the employer asked the employee to sign a second agreement that contained a clause limiting the employee's entitlements to the ESA minimums. The Court of Appeal held that, without fresh consideration, the agreement did not displace the implied term of reasonable notice contained in the offer letter.
<P1><EM>Holland</EM>, at paras 1, 11, 49, 50, 55.</P1></P>
<P>49. In Ariss' case, there was no implied term of reasonable notice in his contract of employment with NORR in 2013, or at any other point in time. The parties agreed to rebut the presumption of reasonable notice at the beginning of Ariss' employment with NORR in 2002, and the terms of the 2013 Amendment were agreed before Ariss transitioned to part-time hours. The fact that Ariss began working part-time hours on July 15, 2013, before signing the 2013 Amendment, is not relevant in the circumstances.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>D.</N><TI>PUBLIC POLICY SUPPORTS NORR'S POSITION</TI>
<P>50. The policy issues outlined in <EM>Machtinger</EM> and referred to by Ariss are not relevant. This is not a case where an employer drafted a termination provision that fails to comply with the ESA and the only sanction faced is an order that the employer comply with the ESA. NORR drafted a termination provision that complied with the minimum notice period prescribed in the ESA. In the motion judge's words, Ariss &ldquo;is not an unsophisticated business person&rdquo;. Ariss agreed to the termination provision, and understood that it applied throughout his employment with NORR. The resulting outcome is an order that NORR provide Ariss with the termination entitlements as agreed between Ariss and NORR and documented in his employment agreement.
<P1><EM>Machtinger</EM>, <EM>supra</EM> para 3, at para 33.</P1>
<P1>Judgment, para 77, at ABCO, Tab 7, p 43.</P1></P>
<P>51. The motion judge properly held that the presumption of common law notice had been rebutted and Ariss is only entitled to notice of termination in accordance with the ESA. There is no reason to interfere with the motion judge's decision.</P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>APPEAL ISSUE TWO: Rule 49 of the <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM> should govern costs at first instance.</TI>
<P>52. NORR agrees that Rule 49 of the <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM>, R.R.O. 1990, Reg. 194, should govern costs at first instance, dependant on the outcome of the appeal and cross-appeal.</P></BLOCK2></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="IV">PART IV&mdash;ISSUES RAISED IN CROSS-APPEAL</TI>
<P>53. The cross-appeal raises the following issue: if this Court finds that Ariss is entitled to common law notice of the termination of his employment, did the motion judge err by failing to address the issue of mitigation?</P>
<BLOCK2><TI>CROSS-APPEAL ISSUE: If Ariss is entitled to common law notice of the termination of his employment, the motion judge erred in failing to address the issue of mitigation.</TI>
<P>54. If this Court finds that the motion judge erred in holding that Ariss is only entitled to notice of termination in accordance with the ESA, NORR submits that the motion judge erred in law by making a determination on Ariss' reasonable notice period, but failing to address the issue of mitigation.</P>
<P>55. With respect to the issue of Ariss' failure to mitigate, the motion judge stated:
<QUOTE><P>NORR's position is that if Ariss is found to be entitled to common law notice then (a) a finding should be made that Ariss breached his obligation to mitigate his damages, and (b) the damages to which Ariss is entitled must be reduced accordingly. NORR submits that the issue of mitigation is not appropriate for determination by way of a motion for summary judgment. NORR argues that Ariss has not met the onus he must meet to demonstrate that the mitigation issue does not require a trial.</P></QUOTE>
<P1>Judgment, para 115, at ABCO, Tab 7, p 49.</P1></P>
<P>56. The motion judge then held that, in light of the finding that Ariss had contracted out of common law notice provisions, it was not necessary to determine the issue of Ariss' alleged failure to mitigate. The motion judge's failure to consider the issue of mitigation is an error of law and the standard of review is correctness.
<P1>Judgment, para 116, at ABCO, Tab 7, p 49.</P1>
<P1><EM>Housen</EM>, <EM>supra</EM> para 39, at para 8.</P1></P>
<P>57. A wrongfully dismissed employee has a duty to take all reasonable steps to mitigate his or her damages and reduce the amount payable by the employer. Where the plaintiff's efforts to mitigate damages are contested, reasonable notice is a triable issue that is not appropriate for summary judgment.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Michaels v Red Deer College</SOC><YEAR>1975</YEAR><CITE>[1976] 2 SCR 324</CITE><PARANUM>10</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Anderson v Cardinal Health Canada Inc</SOC><CITE>2013 ONSC 5226</CITE><PARANUM>7, 10, 16-17</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Thorne v Hudson's Bay Co</SOC><CITE>2011 ONSC 6010</CITE><PARANUM>27-28</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P1></P>
<P>58. Ariss made insufficient efforts to mitigate his damages. Ariss claims to have &ldquo;proactively approached some architectural firms&rdquo; in Kingston, but waited until November 2016&mdash;more than eight months after his employment with NORR was terminated&mdash;to contact them.
<P1>Ariss Affidavit, para 57, at Compendium, Tab 1, p 9.</P1>
<P1>Ariss Affidavit, Exhibit Q, at Compendium, Tab 1-Q, pp 33-34.</P1></P>
<P>59. Ariss made minimal efforts to find a new architectural position in Kingston (the city where he resides). Ariss has not sought the assistance of a recruitment agency or updated his skills by learning basic architecture software, which he knows would make him more marketable.</P>
<P>60. A dismissed employee will have failed to take reasonable steps to mitigate where they do not look for jobs outside of a single town that has few employment opportunities in the employee's profession. Ariss has almost exclusively searched for jobs in Kingston, which is a very small architecture market. Ariss has acknowledged that, by December 2016, he knew it was unlikely that he would get a job in Kingston as an architect, yet he did not expand his search for architectural positions. Ariss did not search for non-architectural positions anywhere.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Birnbaum v Lamda Mercantile Corp</SOC><CITE>1977 CarswellOnt 2883</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>[1977] 1 ACWS 394</CITE></CORRELAT></CASEREF> at para 16 (ON HCJ)</P1></P>
<P>61. NORR has shown that suitable job opportunities have been available to Ariss in Ottawa since his dismissal. Ariss has admitted to seeing job opportunities that he is likely qualified for, but the opportunities are located outside of Kingston and Ariss has not applied for any opportunities outside of Kingston.</P>
<P>62. Accordingly, if Ariss is entitled to common law notice, the motion judge erred in failing to address mitigation, including whether or not the issue was appropriate for summary judgment, or whether a trial is required.</P></BLOCK2></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="V">PART V&mdash;ORDER REQUESTED</TI>
<P>63. NORR respectfully requests an order:
<P1>(a) that the appeal be dismissed; and</P1>
<P1>(b) for the costs of the appeal and cross-appeal on a substantial indemnity basis.</P1></P>
<P>64. In the alternative, if the appeal is granted, NORR respectfully requests an order:
<P1>(a) that the cross-appeal be granted;</P1>
<P1>(b) declaring that Ariss breached his obligation to mitigate his damages and, if Ariss is entitled to damages in excess of his ESA entitlement, the damages must be reduced accordingly;</P1>
<P1>(c) fixing the reasonable notice period to reflect Ariss' failure to mitigate his damages; and</P1>
<P1>(d) for the costs of the appeal and cross-appeal on a substantial indemnity basis.</P1></P>
<P>65. In the further alternative, if the appeal is granted, NORR respectfully requests an order:
<P1>(a) that the cross-appeal be granted;</P1>
<P1>(b) directing that the issue of mitigation proceed to trial expeditiously, pursuant to Rule 20.05 of the <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM>, R.R.O. 1990, Reg. 194; or</P1>
<P1>(c) remitting the issue of mitigation to the motion judge for determination; and</P1>
<P1>(d) for the costs of the appeal and cross-appeal on a substantial indemnity basis.</P1></P>
<P><BOLD>ALL OF WHICH IS RESPECTFULLY SUBMITTED</BOLD> this 9<SUP>th</SUP> day of August, 2018</P>
