<BLOCK1><TI>FACTUM OF THE RESPONDENT BY CROSS-APPEAL (JOHN DAVID ARISS)</TI>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="I">PART I&mdash;OVERVIEW</TI>
<P>1. Justice Corthorn determined that the Appellant and Respondent by Cross-Appeal, John David Ariss (&ldquo;Ariss&rdquo;), did not have an entitlement to reasonable notice of the termination of his employment, but stated in her decision that, if he did, the reasonable notice period would be 22 months.</P>
<P>2. Since the motion judge did not find a reasonable notice entitlement, she explained that it was not necessary to make a determination of whether or not the Respondent and Appellant by Cross-Appeal, NORR Limited Architects and Engineers (&ldquo;NORR&rdquo;), had demonstrated a failure by Ariss to mitigate his damages and, if so, if any reduction should be made to his common law entitlement.</P>
<P>3. It is not in dispute that the 34 weeks of termination and severance pay that Ariss has already been awarded pursuant to the <EM>Employment Standards Act</EM> is not subject to the duty to mitigate, but any reasonable notice income in excess of that amount is.</P>
<P>4. Fulsome submissions on the issue of mitigation were made to the motion judge by both parties.</P>
<P>5. Ariss has never disputed NORR's assertion that the issue of mitigation must be determined in the event that he is successful in his appeal and is entitled to reasonable notice of the termination of his employment, but states that he has met his mitigation obligations and that he has an entitlement to a full 22 months of lost income, less amounts already awarded.</P>
<P>6. While the motion judge is in a position to decide this matter, given that full submissions are required to respond to this Cross-Appeal, Ariss consents to the Court of Appeal determining the issue, notwithstanding his position that the Cross-Appeal added unnecessary cost to the process.</P>
<P>7. As the 22 month notice period has now passed, Ariss proposes to credit NORR for any mitigation earnings in that reasonable notice period beyond his statutory entitlements.</P>
<P>8. NORR did not raise the issue of the suitability of summary judgment to the determination of mitigation in its Notice of Cross-Appeal, nor did it request a trial of the issue or propose returning this narrow issue to the motion judge for determination. It only raised the question of whether it had proven a failure to mitigate damages and requested the Court of Appeal address the matter.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="II">PART II&mdash;FACTS</TI>
<BLOCK3><TI>Judgment</TI>
<P>9. Justice Corthorn explained, &ldquo;The request for a finding of 22 months' notice is at the low end of the range. I find the request to be reasonable. If Ariss were entitled to common law notice (and I find he is not so entitled), the notice period would be 22 months.&rdquo;
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Ariss v. NORR Limited Architects &amp; Engineers</SOC><CITE>2018 ONSC 620</CITE></CASEREF> <BOLD>[Judgment], para 104 at Appeal Book and Compendium [ABCO] Tab 7, p. 47.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>10. Respecting mitigation, Justice Corthorn summarized NORR's position in the motion as follows: &ldquo;NORR's position is that if Ariss is found to be entitled to common law notice then (a) a finding should be made that Ariss breached his obligation to mitigate his damages, and (b) the damages to which Ariss is entitled must be reduced accordingly.&rdquo;
<P1><BOLD>Judgment para 115 at ABCO Tab 7, p. 49.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>11. Given that Justice Corthorn did not find that Ariss is entitled to common law notice, she found that it was not necessary to determine the question of mitigation. Effectively, she understood that mitigation would be relevant only if there was a common law reasonable notice entitlement. All parties agree this is the case.
<P1><BOLD>Judgment para 116 at ABCO Tab 7, p. 49.</BOLD></P1></P></BLOCK3>
