<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="III">PART III&mdash;ARGUMENT RE: ISSUES RAISED BY NORR</TI>
<BLOCK3 LABEL="Issue"><N><UNDER>1</UNDER></N><TI><UNDER>Is the determination of mitigation suitable for summary judgment?</UNDER></TI>
<BLOCK4><TI>Suitable for Summary Judgment</TI>
<P>60. NORR did not raise the issue of the suitability of summary judgment to the determination of mitigation in its Notice of Cross-Appeal, nor did it seek an order that a trial be required or that the motion judge determine the issue. As such, it should be prohibited from raising the issue or seeking associated relief.
<P1><BOLD>Rule 61.08(2) and 61.08(3)&mdash;<EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM>, R.R.O. 1990, Regulation 194 [<EM>Rules</EM>], at Schedule B.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>61. Regardless, the determination of common law reasonable notice, as impacted by mitigation, is appropriate in a summary judgment forum. The court in <CASEREF><SOC>Maasland v. City of Toronto</SOC><CITE>2015 ONSC 7598 (CanLII)</CITE></CASEREF> <BOLD>[<EM>Maasland</EM>],</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Markoulakis v. SNC-Lavalin Inc.</SOC><CITE>2015 ONSC 1081 (CanLII)</CITE></CASEREF> <BOLD>[<EM>Markoulakis</EM>],</BOLD> and <CASEREF><SOC>Vinette v. Delta Printing Limited</SOC><CITE>2017 ONSC 182</CITE></CASEREF> <BOLD>[<EM>Vinette</EM>],</BOLD> amongst others all found this to be an appropriate forum for the determination of reasonable notice. Each considered mitigation.</P>
<P>62. Justice MacLeod in <BOLD><EM>Vinette</EM></BOLD> wrote:
<QUOTE><P>There have now been a series of cases in this court holding that summary judgment is a process that may be particularly suited for determination of notice periods in cases of termination without cause. The law was reviewed by Justice Hackland in <CASEREF><SOC>Beatty v. Best Theratronics Ltd.</SOC></CASEREF> and his decision to grant summary judgment in that case was upheld by the Court of Appeal...He was also able to determine the question of mitigation.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Vinette v. Delta Printing Limited</SOC><CITE>2017 ONSC 182</CITE><PARANUM>25</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P1></P>
<P>63. The cases cited by NORR suggesting that the determination of mitigation requires a trial all pre-date the Supreme Court of Canada's decision in <CASEREF><SOC>Hryniak v. Mauldin</SOC><CITE>[2014] 1 SCR 87 (CanLII)</CITE></CASEREF>, which changed the legal landscape surrounding the suitability of summary judgment. NORR had the opportunity to cross-examine on the Ariss affidavits. There is no reason that the law cannot be applied to the facts. A trial would add a disproportionate amount of additional costs and further delay the determination of this matter.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Hryniak v. Mauldin</SOC><CITE>2014 SCC 17 (CanLII)</CITE><PARANUM>49</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P1>
<P1><BOLD>Rule 20.04&mdash;<EM>Rules</EM> at Schedule B.</BOLD></P1></P></BLOCK4></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3 LABEL="Issue"><N><UNDER>2</UNDER></N><TI><UNDER>What is the standard of review?</UNDER></TI>
<BLOCK4><TI>Standard of Review</TI>
<P>64. The Court of Appeal is being asked to perform the role of the motion judge, who heard and has before her all evidence and argument on the issue of mitigation. The motion judge did not err on the issue of mitigation, but simply did not make the determination on the basis that it was a moot point in the context of her other findings. It is Ariss' position that Justice Corthorn erred on the issue of his entitlement to common law reasonable notice of the termination of his employment, and, as such, the issue of mitigation must now be determined.</P>
<P>65. Given that Ariss was required to respond to the Cross-Appeal, it is most efficient for the Court of Appeal now to determine the issue, however there is no decision to review. Rather, the Court of Appeal is effectively hearing this matter at first instance and standard of review is not applicable. The same effect would be had by sending the issue back to the motion judge for determination; however that may now cause further delay.</P>
<P>66. It is not the reasonable notice determination that would change in the context of a mitigation assessment. Justice Corthorn is correct on the 22 month number, which was not contested in first instance and cannot be contested now. Rather, consideration of mitigation determines if the 22 month damages award should be reduced by a failure to meet those obligations. Ariss states that NORR has failed to demonstrate that a reduction is appropriate.</P></BLOCK4></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3 LABEL="Issue"><N><UNDER>3</UNDER></N><TI><UNDER>Has NORR demonstrated a failure by Ariss to mitigate his damages?</UNDER></TI>
<BLOCK4><TI>Onus of Proof</TI>
<P>67. An employer has the burden of proving a failure to mitigate damages.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Markoulakis</EM> at para 7.</BOLD></P1></P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><TI>No Work in Kingston</TI>
<P>68. No suitable work opportunities for Ariss arose in Kingston or the surrounding area during the reasonable notice period, though Ariss demonstrated significant efforts to reach out to local businesses and contacts to explore opportunities. Preparing his resume, seeking out reference letters, researching jobs online and in the newspaper, proactively contacting architectural firms and other businesses in the area, networking, and expanding his search to full-time roles and project management roles collectively demonstrated reasonable efforts on his part to mitigate his damages.</P>
<P>69. NORR accepts that architect job opportunities in Kingston were difficult to come by and that existing firms were struggling to maintain their businesses. NORR did not last in the market and closed its doors.
<P1><BOLD>Souter Affidavit para 28, 37 at RXCO Tab 2, p. 39, 41 and EB Tab 2, p. 69, 71</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>Gerstmar Affidavit, para 15 at RXCO Tab 3, p. 67 and EB Tab 3, p. 143.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>70. NORR has not suggested or demonstrated that there were any suitable roles in Kingston or the surrounding area for Ariss to apply to and effectively acknowledged that there were none. As such, they have not met the onus of demonstrating a failure to mitigate in Kingston and area.</P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><TI>Commute Limitations</TI>
<P>71. Rather, by submitting job postings in the area, NORR has suggested that Ariss should either commute or relocate to Ottawa.
<P1><BOLD>Souter Affidavit para 38 at RXCO Tab 2, p. 42 and EB Tab 2, p. 72.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>Souter Affidavit Exhibit L at RXCO Tab 2L, p. 44 and EB Tab 2L, p. 119.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>72. Even if Ariss met the qualifications for the roles in Ottawa proposed by NORR, which he does not, it would not be reasonable for him to apply for them given the distance between Kingston and Ottawa.
<P1><BOLD>Ariss Reply Affidavit, para 30&ndash;36 at RXCO Tab 4, p.73 and EB Tab 4, p. 165.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>73. In <BOLD><EM>Maasland</EM></BOLD> the court rejected an employer's argument that an individual should have applied for a job 50 km away. The Court reasoned, &ldquo;It was reasonable for her not to pursue a job that would, if she had got it, have involved a significant daily commute.&rdquo;
<P1><BOLD><EM>Maasland</EM> at para 43.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>74. Ariss states that he was likewise not obligated to apply for jobs in Ottawa, some 200 km away; Toronto, approximately 250 km away; or Sudbury, approximately 600 km away.</P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><TI>Relocation Unreasonable</TI>
<P>75. The Court of Appeal in <CASEREF><SOC>Peet v. Babcock &amp; Wilcox Industries Ltd.</SOC><CITE>2001 CanLII 24077</CITE><COURTJUR>ON CA</COURTJUR></CASEREF> found that, given an employee's age of 53 and his ties to his community, he could not be expected to move to accept another position with his current employer.</P>
<P>76. Ultimately, the court noted, &ldquo;The respondent's efforts at mitigation cannot be classified as unreasonable simply because his actions did not neglect all other interests while focusing exclusively on his short-term obligation to mitigate damages for the sake of his former employer.&rdquo;
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Peet v. Babcock &amp; Wilcox Industries Ltd.</SOC><CITE>2001 CanLII 24077</CITE><COURTJUR>ON CA</COURTJUR></CASEREF> <BOLD>at para 8.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>77. The Court in <CASEREF><SOC>Kees Van Schalkwyk v. Hyundai Auto Canada Inc.</SOC><CITE>1995 CanLII 7294</CITE><COURTJUR>ON SC</COURTJUR></CASEREF> <BOLD>[<EM>Kees</EM>]</BOLD> surveyed case law surrounding relocation and mitigation, asking whether an employee is required to take a position that will involve a major relocation. Ultimately, the employee in Kees was not required to take either of two long distance job offers.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Kees Van Schalkwyk v. Hyundai Auto Canada Inc.</SOC><CITE>1995 CanLII 7294</CITE><COURTJUR>ON SC</COURTJUR></CASEREF> <BOLD>[<EM>Kees</EM>] para 66.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>78. It cited <CASEREF><SOC>Curry v. Lakeland Library Region</SOC><YEAR>1980</YEAR><CITE>3 Sask. R. 364</CITE><COURTJUR>Q.B</COURTJUR></CASEREF>, where an employee worked in the same community, for the same employer, for 30 years, and had established a family home. Relocation and search elsewhere at the age of 55 was not required.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Kees</EM> para 52.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>79. The Court in <BOLD><EM>Kees</EM></BOLD> noted, &ldquo;certainly family reasons are considered by the court in deciding whether the plaintiff was acting reasonably in refusing to move&rdquo;. They cited David Harris' text, <UNDER>Wrongful Dismissal</UNDER>, 1990 ed. (Toronto: Carswell 1989), at 4-253, which lists the obligation to care for an elderly dependent as one such family reason.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Kees</EM> para 60, 61.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>80. Ariss was 62 at the time of his dismissal. He states that moving would impact his wife's job; his long term ties to Kingston, where they own a home; their ability to care for his wife's elderly father; and their proximity to their daughter. Relocating would be highly disruptive and costly.</P></BLOCK4></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3 LABEL="Issue"><N><UNDER>4</UNDER></N><TI><UNDER>What reduction in damages is appropriate, if any?</UNDER></TI>
<BLOCK4><TI>No Reduction Justified</TI>
<P>81. Ariss states that he has acted reasonably to mitigate his damages. Accordingly, no reduction to the 22 month notice period is justified, particularly where the notice period awarded was determined to be &ldquo;at the low end of the range&rdquo; and he has made considerable efforts to secure alternative employment in a challenging market.</P></BLOCK4></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="IV">PART IV&mdash;ARGUMENT RE: ISSUES RAISED BY ARISS</TI>
<BLOCK3 LABEL="Issue"><N><UNDER>1</UNDER></N><TI><UNDER>How should the Court address the issue of mitigation for the portion of the notice period that occurred after Ariss' Reply Affidavit?</UNDER></TI>
<BLOCK4><TI>Balance Of Notice Period</TI>
<P>82. Although there is no evidence of Ariss' mitigation efforts between April 2017 and November 2017 because his Reply affidavit was due at the end of March 2017, it is appropriate for the Court of Appeal to order loss of income in lump sum for the full notice period, less amounts already paid, and less amounts earned in mitigation between April 2017 and November 2017.</P>
<P>83. The Court of Appeal has demonstrated a willingness and ability to uphold notice awards absent further evidence on mitigation efforts where a summary judgment motion was heard prior to the expiration of the reasonable notice period.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Markoulakis</EM> para 9.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>84. In <CASEREF><SOC>Bernier v. Nygard International Partnership</SOC><CITE>2013 ONCA 780 (CanLII)</CITE></CASEREF>, the Court of Appeal affirmed that it was appropriate for the motion judge to order a lump sum in lieu of notice and require that any earnings of the employee during the notice period be placed in a trust for the employer.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Bernier v. Nygard International Partnership</SOC><CITE>2013 ONCA 78 (CanLII)</CITE><PARANUM>6</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P1></P>
<P>85. The same approach was taken at first instance in <CASEREF><SOC>Paquette v. TeraGo Networks Inc.</SOC><CITE>2016 ONCA 618 (CanLII)</CITE></CASEREF>, as summarized in the appeal decision: &ldquo;He found that the appellant had made reasonable efforts to mitigate his damages and directed him to account for any mitigation earnings for the balance of the reasonable notice period, with such earnings subject to a trust in favour of the respondent.&rdquo;
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Paquette v. TeraGo Networks Inc.</SOC><CITE>2016 ONCA 618 (CanLII)</CITE><PARANUM>3</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P1></P>
<P>86. In the instant matter, the notice period had not lapsed to the date of Ariss Reply Affidavit or to the date of the summary judgment motion. As of the Reply Affidavit, Ariss had not earned any mitigation income.
<P1><BOLD>Ariss Reply Affidavit para 50 at RXCO Tab 4, p. 75 and EB Tab 4, p. 167.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>87. There was no opportunity for new or further evidence to be brought to the Court of Appeal respecting Ariss' mitigation efforts between April 2017 and November 2017.</P>
<P>88. It has now been more than 22 months since Ariss' dismissal in January 2016.</P>
<P>89. Given that the notice period has now expired, it is appropriate for NORR to pay Ariss a lump sum equivalent to 22 months of income, less amounts already paid, less any mitigation amounts that Ariss has earned since his Reply Affidavit.</P></BLOCK4></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="V">PART V&mdash;RELIEF SOUGHT</TI>
<P>90. Ariss requests an Order that he is entitled to 22 months of income, less amounts already paid, less any mitigation income earned between April 2017 and November 2017.</P>
<P>91. He seeks costs of the Cross-Appeal on a substantial indemnity basis, as this matter could have been sent back to the motion judge for determination.</P>
<P><BOLD>ALL OF WHICH IS RESPECTFULLY SUBMITTED</BOLD> this 17<SUP>th</SUP> day of August, 2018.</P>
